lish predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705178,"age":2,"year":"1002","julianDay":2087033,"title":"St. Brice's Day Massacre","description":"King Aethelred ordered all Danish men in England to be killed. It is unknown how many Danes were killed due to this order.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705179,"age":13,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705181,"age":35,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":66,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Waterville I was born about 1000, in Sussex, England. He had at least 1 son with Faelis verch Llewlen. He died about 1085, in England, at the age of 87."},"et":{"about 1000–about 1085":"umbes 1000–umbes 1085","1004–Female":"1004–Surnud","1022–1085":"1022–1085","1000–1085":"1000–1085","about 1085":"umbes 1085","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1002":"1002","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1085":"1085","about 1000":"umbes 1000","England":"England","Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Westhampnett, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1000–about 1085":"noin 1000–noin 1085","1004–Female":"1004–Kuollut","1022–1085":"1022–1085","1000–1085":"1000–1085","about 1085":"noin 1085","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1002":"1002","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1085":"1085","about 1000":"noin 1000","England":"England","Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Westhampnett, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1000–about 1085":"environ 1000–environ 1085","1004–Female":"1004–Décédée","1022–1085":"1022–1085","1000–1085":"1000–1085","about 1085":"environ 1085","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1002":"1002","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1085":"1085","about 1000":"environ 1000","England":"Angleterre","Westhampnett, Sussex, England":"Westhampnett, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleter